'''Migukurumitama Shrine''' (美具久留御魂神社) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in {{ill|Tondabayashi|ja|富田林市|12=draft|12=draft}}, [[Osaka Prefecture]]. It is an {{ill|historic shrine|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}} and was formerly Ranked as a {{ill|gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft|12=draft}} under the [[modern shrine Ranking system]]. The shrine is also selected as one of the {{ill|100 Green Selections of Osaka|ja|大阪みどりの百選|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pref.osaka.lg.jp/midorikikaku/toshiryokka/hyakusenn.html|title=Osaka 100 Green Selections|publisher=Osaka Prefecture|accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref> It is also referred to as the "Shimono Suibun Shrine" (下水分社) and, along with {{ill|Tatsuta Shrine|ja|建水分神社|1=Take Mikumari Shrine|12=draft|12=draft}} (the Kamisuibun Shrine in {{ill|Chihayaakasaka|ja|千早赤阪村|12=draft|12=draft}}) and {{ill|Nishikori Shrine|ja|錦織神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (in Tondabayashi), it is one of the "Three Mikumari Shrines of {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|河内国|12=draft|12=draft}}."
== Enshrined Deities == * '''Primary Deity:''' Migukurumitama no Ōkami (美具久留御魂大神) – The {{ill|Aramitama|ja|荒魂・和魂|12=draft|12=draft}} (rough spirit) of {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主命|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is believed to represent a water deity, deriving its name from "Mikukurumitama" (Water Swimming Spirit). * '''Additional Deities:''' ** {{ill|Mikumari|fr|Mikumari|lt=Amemikumari no Kami|ja|天水分神|12=draft|12=draft}} (Heavenly Mikumari Deity) ** {{ill|Mizuhanome|lt=Mizuhanome no Mikoto|ja|弥都波迺売命|12=draft|12=draft}} ** {{ill|Mikumari|fr|Mikumari|lt=Kuni no Mikumari no Kami|ja|国水分神|12=draft|12=draft}} ** {{ill|Suseri-Hime|lt=Suseribime no Mikoto|ja|須勢理比売命|12=draft|12=draft}} ** {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花咲耶比売神|12=draft|12=draft}}
== History == === Foundation === According to tradition, the shrine was founded in the 10th year of Emperor Sujin's reign (88 BCE). A giant serpent frequently appeared in the area, leading the emperor to identify it as the aramitama of Ōkuninushi. He dispatched {{ill|Izumo Furune|ja|出雲振根|12=draft|12=draft}} to enshrine the deity, borrowing sacred objects from {{ill|Izumo Taisha|ja|杵築大社|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Japanese Place Name Dictionary|publisher=Heibonsha|year=1986}}</ref>
In Emperor Sujin's 62nd year, an oracle declared that "Mikukurumitama" should be the deity's name, and the shrine was established to house this deity alongside four others.
=== Historical Records === The shrine may correspond to the "Kawachi Province Wani Shrine" mentioned in 850 CE, where the deity's Rank was raised to {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|ja|従五位上|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|12=draft|12=draft}}. During the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, it also served as a clan shrine for the {{ill|Kusunoki family|ja|楠木氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, who venerated the shrine as their ancestral deity.
The shrine was burned down during the {{ill|Siege of Akasaka|ja|赤坂城の戦い|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1331 but was later rebuilt under the support of {{ill|Kusunoki Masashige|ja|楠木正成|12=draft|12=draft}}. In 1585, it was again destroyed during the {{ill|Kishū Campaign|ja|紀州征伐|12=draft|12=draft}} by {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|12=draft|12=draft}}. The current main shrine was reconstructed in 1660.
The shrine was designated as a gōsha in 1872 during the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Shrine Grounds == The shrine grounds include the following structures: * '''Main Shrine (Honden):''' Rebuilt in 1660. * '''Upper Worship Hall (Kami-haiden):''' Rebuilt in 1660. * '''Lower Worship Hall (Shimo-haiden):''' * '''Treasure Hall (Saigu-kura):''' * '''Gates and Torii:''' * '''Miyajinja Uramayama Kofun Group:''' Includes a keyhole-shaped kofun (58 m long) believed to be from the early {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Uramayama Kofun Explanation Board|publisher=Educational Board of Tondabayashi|accessdate=2020-08-28}}</ref>
== Subsidiary Shrines == * {{ill|Kumano Takahira Shrine|ja|熊野貴平神社|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Nagi Shrine|ja|南木神社|12=draft|12=draft}} – Dedicated to the Kusunoki family. * {{ill|Kuni no Ichi Shrine|ja|皇大神社|12=draft|12=draft}}
== Annual Festivals == The shrine's annual festival is held on the third Friday of October.
